CIMON.

Simonis—Cimon, after his father's death, imprisoned in his stead, gains his freedom through the generous act of his sister (1). He quickly gains for himself the most prominent position in the state and performs great deeds (2). He is banished by popular vote (ostracism); recalled five years later, he restores peace to Greece; then having thoroughly defeated the PersianS, he dies of disease in the island of Cyprus (3).
